# OCR Pipeline (pdf2image + pytesseract)

## Context

`src/bot/ocr.py` converts downloaded PDFs into plain text via image-based OCR. This is the only module that touches PDF processing.

## Patterns

- Use `pdf2image.convert_from_path()` to get a list of PIL Images, one per page
- Use `pytesseract.image_to_string()` on each image
- Default DPI is 300; accept it as a parameter for tuning
- Skip empty pages (only append if `text.strip()` is truthy)
- Join pages with `"\n\n"` to preserve page boundaries

```python
images = convert_from_path(pdf_path, dpi=dpi)
for image in images:
    text = pytesseract.image_to_string(image)
    if text.strip():
        pages.append(text.strip())
return "\n\n".join(pages)
```

## Anti-patterns

- Do not use `PyPDF2` / `pdfplumber` text extraction -- the PDFs may be scanned images, so OCR is required
- Do not write intermediate image files to disk; `convert_from_path` returns in-memory PIL images
- Do not silently swallow OCR errors; let exceptions propagate so the caller sees failures

## Best Practices

- If OCR quality is poor, increase DPI (e.g., 400-600) at the cost of speed
- Consider `pytesseract.image_to_string(image, lang='eng')` if non-English text appears
- Keep this module focused on PDF-to-text; do not add LLM or browser logic here
